{{Infobox religious building | name = {{nihongo|'''Yahiko jinja'''|弥彦神社||}} | image = Yahiko shrine.JPG | caption = Yahiko Shrine | map_type = Japan Niigata Prefecture#Japan | map_alt = | coordinates = {{coord|37|42|23.7|N|138|49|33.9|E|region:JP-15_type:landmark|display=title,inline}} | map_relief = 1 | map_size = | map_caption = | religious_affiliation = [[Shinto]] | type = | deity = Ame-no-Kaguyama-no-Mikoto | founded_by = | established = | date_destroyed = | location = [[Yahiko, Niigata]], Japan | website = {{Official|1=http://www.yahiko-jinjya.or.jp}} | architecture_style = | festival = | leadership = }} {{nihongo|'''Yahiko jinja'''|弥彦神社||}}, also known as '''Iyahiko-jinja''' is a [[Shinto shrine]] in the village of [[Yahiko, Niigata|Yahiko]], [[Nishikanbara District, Niigata|Nishikanbara District]], [[Niigata Prefecture]], Japan. It is the ''[[ichinomiya]]'' of [[Echigo Province]]<ref>[http://eos.kokugakuin.ac.jp/modules/xwords/images/uploads/EOS070712Ab.pdf "Nationwide List of ''Ichinomiya''," p. 2]; retrieved 2012-3-13.</ref>. Under the pre-World War II [[Modern system of ranked Shinto Shrines]], the shrine was classified as a national shrine of the middle rank (国幣中社, ''kokuhei chusha''). The shrine's annual festival is held on February 2. This solemn shrine standing at the tranquil foot of a mountain is popularly known as a power spot for love and good fortune<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://planetyze.com/en/japan/niigata/yahiko-shrine/information|title=About Yahiko Shrine - Niigata Travel Guide {{!}} Planetyze|website=Planetyze|language=en|access-date=2017-10-14}}</ref>
The shrine is located within [[Sado-Yahiko-Yoneyama Quasi-National Park]] and is on the eastern base of [[Mount Yahiko]],<ref>Japan National Tourism Organization (JNTO), [http://www.jnto.go.jp/eng/location/regional/niigata/yahikosan.html "Mt. Yahiko Area"]; retrieved 2012-10-24.</ref> a 634-meter [[Sacred mountains|sacred mountain]] which forms the ''[[shintai]]'' of the shrine.
==History== The foundation date of Yahiko Shrine is prehistoric, and the shrine was referred to as "ancient" in a poem even in the [[Nara period]] ''[[Man'yōshū]]''. Yahiko Shrine was thus already well established when a new building was created by Imperial edict in the 8th century.<ref name="village">[http://www.vill.yahiko.niigata.jp/ Yahiko Village website], [http://www.vill.yahiko.niigata.jp/language/main-kankou_E.html "Sightseeing Information--Yahiko Shrine"]; retrieved 2012-10-24.</ref> The enshrined ''[[kami]]'' is {{nihongo|'''Ame-no-Kaguyama-no-Mikoto'''|天香山命||}} appears in the ''[[Kojiki]]'', and is said to have arrived in Echigo from the heavens to teach the inhabitants fishing, rice cultivation, salt production and the other basics of farming,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://planetyze.com/en/japan/niigata/yahiko-shrine/information|title=About Yahiko Shrine - Niigata Travel Guide {{!}} Planetyze|website=Planetyze|language=en|access-date=2017-10-14}}</ref>.<ref>JNTO, [http://www.jnto.go.jp/eng/location/spot/shritemp/yahikojinja.html "Yahiko-jinja Shrine"]; Kotodamaya.com, [http://www.kotodamaya.com/yahiko-jinja/ "Yahiko Jinja"]; retrieved 2012-10-24.</ref>
The subsequent history of the shrine is uncertain and often contradictory, as most old records have been lost in fires and other disasters over the years. The shrine was well patronised by the military class, and the shrine treasury has a [[Muromachi period]] [[Ōdachi]] [[Japanese sword]] which is an [[Important Cultural Property of Japan]] as well as amor and swords donated by [[Minamoto no Yoriie]], [[Minamoto no Yoshitsune]] and [[Uesugi Kenshin]]. During the [[Edo period]], the ''[[daimyō]]'' of [[Takada Domain]], [[Matsudaira Tadateru]] granted the shrine estates with a ''[[kokudaka]]'' of 500 ''koku''.
The present shrine structures were rebuilt in 1916. The earlier shrine buildings were destroyed by a 1912 fire which started in the village.<ref name="village"/>
==Related pages== * [[List of Shinto shrines in Japan]] * [[Modern system of ranked Shinto Shrines]]
==References== {{reflist}}
==External links == {{Commons category-inline|Yahiko-jinja}} * [http://www.yahiko-jinjya.or.jp Official home page] {{ja}}
{{Shinto shrine}}
